<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / International Company News: Argentina reaps Dollars 3bn in
record oil group sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER and JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Argentine government has sold Dollars 3.04bn of stock in the state oil
and gas company YPF in one of the world's largest privatisations. It is the
biggest single equity offering from the developing world.
With the initial public offering heavily over-subscribed, the government was
able to increase the number of shares available from 125m to 160m, or to 45
per cent of the company. The stock was priced at Dollars 19, at the upper
end of the previously-announced range of Dollars 17 to Dollars 20.
Argentina's success will be seen as proof of its acceptance by international
financial markets, and as a vital fillip to its economic reform programme.
The government will use the proceeds from the privatisation to pay off debts
owed to pensioners, thus giving the ruling party's fortunes a lift in the
run-up to October's Congressional elections.
Brokers said demand for YPF was especially high in the US, with its original
allotment of over Dollars 1bn more than four times over-subscribed. In
Argentina, caution turned into enthusiasm as those willing to invest more
than Dollars 10,000 reportedly bid more than 10 times their allotment.
The privatisation will be concluded when the government sells a second part
of the company to employees and pensioners.
The sale marks the first time a large Latin America country has given up
control of its state oil company, traditionally seen in the region as a
symbol of nationalism and self-sufficiency.
Mexico and Chile, pioneers of economic reform in Latin America, have held on
to their largest state companies, Petroleos Mexicanos and Codelco
respectively.
The transaction was co-ordinated by CS First Boston and Merrill Lynch.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Yacimientos Petroliferos Fascales.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ARZ   Argentina, South America.
</CN>
<XX>
