<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / International Company News: Norwegian shipowner wins control
of Investa
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ANDERS Wilhelmsen, the privately-owned Norwegian shipowner, has acquired
control of Investa, the unlisted Norwegian investment group, for NKr350m
(Dollars 48.8m) from a group of 34 financial creditors.
Investa collapsed last August under the weight of NKr3.4bn in debt, of which
NKr2.8bn was in unsecured loans in the form of debt notes and commercial
paper.
The deal brings Wilco, Wilhelmsen's main subsidiary, an 87.8 per cent stake
in Investa and an 90.2 per cent stake in the Norwegian Golar Nor group,
which owns the Petrojarl oil and gas production testing vessel.
Mr Endre Ording Sund, chief executive of Anders Wilhelmsen, said yesterday
his company planned to develop Golar Nor, which has had six owners in the
past eight years. Mr Sund said several companies had expressed interest in
becoming a joint partner.
The deal also gives the group 80 per cent of the shares of Nydalen Company,
an Oslo bourse-listed real estate company, which has about 500,000 sq m of
property in Norway. Wilhelmsen will also secure control of Nydalen's board.
Wilhelmsen also gets a 47 per cent stake in Euronav, the French shipowner,
in which it will gain a seat on the board.
The deal also brings Wilhelmsen a 7.5 per cent stake in Vard, the Norwegian
cruise and ferry group. Mr Sund said his company intended to be a long-term
investor in Vard, whose shares he feels are considerably under-priced.
Yesterday, Vard's shares closed on the Oslo bourse NKr1.25 lower at
NKr16.25.
Wilhelmsen already holds 50 per cent of Royal Caribbean Cruise Lines, the
world's second-biggest cruise group and Vard's main competitor.
Mr Sund said his company was likely to gain full control of Investa and of
Golar Nor and end expects soon to enter talks with minority creditors.
</TEXT>
