<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / Airtours reacts to OFT inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AIRTOURS, the holiday company, will suggest to the Office of Fair Trading
that tied travel agency chains be required to display notices alerting
customers that staff will probably recommend the parent tour operator's
holidays.
The OFT wrote to travel companies and trade organisations earlier this month
saying it was conducting informal inquiries into links between large
operators and travel agents. Companies have been asked to make submissions
by July 11.
Mr David Crossland, Airtours chairman, said its submission would say that
customers have a right to know whether a travel agent is owned by a tour
operator.
He added that it would be impractical to prohibit the payment of incentives
and commissions to travel agent counter staff by tour operators. He said
staff at Pickfords Travel, the travel agency chain which the group purchased
last year, were paid a pre-tax commission of Pounds 3 for every Airtours
holiday sold. Staff can build up points towards a holiday as an alternative
to the cash payments.
Mr Crossland said the payment of incentives had been happening for decades
and had nothing to do with the recent trend towards vertical integration in
the industry. He recalled that as a travel agency employee in the early
1960s, he had received a holiday on the Costa Brava.
He did not think the OFT would order tour operators to sell their travel
agency chains as it had approved Airtours' purchase of Pickfords.
Airtours, which yesterday announced a half-year pre-tax loss of Pounds 15.9m
after the Pounds 9m cost of its failed bid for Owners Abroad, has bought
Cardiff-based Aspro Travel, the UK's seventh largest tour operator. The
Pounds 20m acquisition follows the purchase of the Hogg Robinson travel
agency chain earlier this month.
He said the purchase of Aspro would strengthen Airtours in Wales, Northern
Ireland and the south-west of England. Aspro's programmes to the eastern
Mediterranean would complement Airtours' strength in the western
Mediterranean and the Canary Islands.
Airtours would retain the Aspro brand name. Its airline, Inter Auropean
Airways would, however, be integrated into the Airtours flight division and
its eight aircraft repainted in the Airtours livery.
Mr Crossland said the enlarged group would have 18 aircraft operating this
summer. This would be reduced to between 14 and 16 by next summer.
Airtours loss after bid costs, Page 18
