<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Unions cool on Scargill threat to
Labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ARTHUR SCARGILL, president of the National Union of Mineworkers, was
isolated by trade unionists yesterday after threatening that Labour's
attempts to reform its links with the union movement could lead to the
setting up of a new political party.
Speaking at his union's annual conference in Scarborough, Mr Scargill said
that if the Labour leader persisted with attempts to diminish the role and
influence of trade unions in the party there was 'a real risk that trade
unions - or some of them - may decide it is time to conceive a new party
which will give the same unequivocal commitment in parliament to our class
that the Tory Party gives to its own.'
Trade unions, he said, should be seeking to strengthen, not weaken the
influence and effectiveness of trade unions inside the Labour party.
Other trade unions - even those opposed to the reforms proposed by Mr John
Smith, Labour leader - quickly distanced themselves from Mr Scargill's
remarks.
His proposals were not taken seriously either by the Labour leadership, with
one official dismissing him as 'an isolated individual.'
The schism has historical parallels - the Miners Federation eschewed links
with the Labour Representation Committee, the precursor to the Labour party,
for almost a decade after its formation in 1900. The miners' union then
sponsored its own MPs.
But yesterday other trade unions reiterated their commitment to the existing
Labour party. A spokesman for the GMB union, whose leader Mr John Edmunds
has been critical of Mr Smith's leadership, said Mr Scargill's remarks were
'unhelpful' and divisive.
Nupe, the public service union, said it was happy that its views were voiced
through Labour's ruling National Executive Committee. 'I think that we would
probably want to distance ourselves from it (Mr Scargill's speech) at the
moment,' said a spokesman.
A spokesman for RMT, the transport union, said there would have to be
'massive changes' for it to abandon the existing Labour party. Mr Jimmy
Knapp, RMT general secretary, told the union's annual conference yesterday
that he supported Labour's existing shadow cabinet, 'warts and all'. The
Trades Union Congress said yesterday it was opposed to any takeover of
privatised pits by Hanson, the Anglo-US conglomerate. The TUC also said it
would be mounting a campaign of 'political and social pressure' to draw
attention to action in the US by the United Mine Workers of America and
Canada. UMWA is striking in the US against the Hanson subsidiary, Peabody,
over job security.
</TEXT>
