<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Action considered over problem
rifle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government is considering taking steps against the suppliers of the
Army's SA80 rifle, recently condemned by MPs on the cross-party defence
committee as 'verging on the shoddy', Viscount Cranborne, a junior defence
minister, said yesterday.
'The question of liability is still under discussion,' he said, adding that
action against the company was a possibil-ity.
The rifle, of which some 332,000 have been supplied or ordered, is made by
Royal Ordnance, which was sold to British Aerospace in 1987.
The defence committee's report listed 32 problems with the SA80, which came
into service in 1985. These included: poor performance in desert conditions;
most left-handed soldiers could not fire it; trigger mechanisms tended to
stick; firing pins broke; bayonets snapped off; and the cleaning kit was
'inadequate'.
Lord Cranborne told peers: 'There were defects in the rifle as originally
supplied - a greater number of defects than we would like to accept.'
But he insisted that, in spite of these, 'by the time it was in service in
the Gulf, properly cleaned, it was clear that its performance was at least
equal to other rifles in use'.
