<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / MP urges refit work for Swan Hunter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT's promise last week to Rosyth naval dockyard of 12 years'
work on warship refits yesterday prompted a call for a guaranteed programme
of work for Swan Hunter, the Tyneside shipbuilder in receivership.
Mr Nick Brown, Labour MP for Newcastle East, last night tabled Commons
questions urging the award to Swan Hunter of a core programme of refits.
Mr Brown said the promise to the Scottish yard of warship work until 2005
had signalled a 'substantial change in what we understood the marketplace to
be'. He added: 'If it's ideologically sound for Devonport and Rosyth to have
core programmes promised, then it must be right for Tyneside.'
Mr Brown said he was not calling for a large programme for Swan Hunter, but
for a 'statement of faith' in it from the government. Three refits are due
to be offered for tender this year or early next year, he said. Awarding
these now to Swan Hunter would be a lifeline, he added.
Reacting to Mr Brown's call, the Ministry of Defence said that last week's
announcement for Rosyth and Devonport was made to confirm the future of the
two dockyards. 'We are running the defence of the realm, not a business of
trying to ensure the future of warship yards,' the department said.
</TEXT>
