<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / 100-channel TV mooted: Digital broadcasting technology set
to transform viewing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK could have as many as 100 television channels without the need for
cable or satellite by using digital technology, the Independent Television
Commission said yesterday.
Such a large number would only be possible, however, if digital broadcasts
from existing transmitters replaced the PAL broadcasts of the four
television channels. PAL is the present analogue broadcasting system used in
the UK.
Introducing a discussion document on digital television yesterday, Mr Peter
Rogers, ITC deputy chief executive, warned that a notice period of at least
10 years would be needed before existing PAL transmissions could be
discontinued.
'Black boxes' would be needed to convert the digital signal and the
commission accepts that it is unrealistic suddenly to tell viewers they will
need a box if they want to continue watching.
Because of the complexity of the issues, the commission favours a gradual
introduction of digital technology with a combination of simulcast - the
retransmission in digital form of the existing channels - plus new services.
In some areas of the country, as many as 20 extra channels of television
could be provided digitally over existing channels in addition to the four
PAL channels - BBC1, BBC2, ITV and Channel 4. However, mainly because of
congestion of PAL frequencies this would be much lower in some of the most
lucrative television areas in the south and south-east.
In some areas there would not be enough spare capacity to simulcast the four
national channels in digital.
'It would be very difficult to go ahead without at least a European standard
in place (for the black box),' Mr Rogers said yesterday.
Yesterday's document states the enormous potential in digital technology for
transforming television.
The commission suggests that the move to terrestrial digital broadcasting
could allow many more viewing options such as channels which concentrate on
comedy in peak time, and others which concentrate on current affairs.
Several channels could be devoted to a football match and viewers could
choose which camera angle to watch from. Channels could be set aside for
more regional news.
The commission will publish a paper on the future of Channel 5 next month
and digital use will be one of the options.
The first full use of digital in Europe is likely to be by FilmNet, the
satellite company broadcasting pay-television to the Benelux countries.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ   United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
