<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / BBC's support services face market testing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BBC will today tell staff that it is moving to a system of market
testing in non-programme making areas such as the management of buildings,
training and transport services.
The aim is to ensure value for money in the corporation's support services
and that the maximum amount of funds goes to programme making.
Market testing, which will become a continual process, will be carried out
by individual BBC departments. It will involve competitive tenders being
sought for work at present done in-house and the possibility of entire areas
of work going to outside contractors.
Mr Michael Starks, controller of BBC services, said yesterday that he
expected the main impact to come from the non-programme-related service
departments reassessing the demand for what they offer following the
introduction of theProducer Choice policy last April. Under this policy
programme producers are able to buy in services from outside the
corporation.
Producers who now have to pay for everything at full cost are trying to
reduce what they pay in overheads.
Mr Starks confirmed that competitive tendering would be used and that
further contracting out of services was a possibility. One area likely to
receive a close look will be buildings management.
Mr Starks insisted that the market-testing exercise was not designed to
reduce the size of the BBC. 'It is about demonstrable value for money for
the licence-payer,' he said.
The result of both a decline in demand for support services at the BBC and
market testing will almost inevitably lead to fewer staff jobs at the
corporation.
BBC staff will also be told that the corporation will help to protect the
terms and conditions of staff whose work goes to private operators in line
with the Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of Employment) Regulations.
</TEXT>
