<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / High-tech future for rustic town
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SMALL town of Kington in Hereford &amp; Worcester is to become the
'high-tech' rural community of the future.
It has been selected for a national pilot scheme to study the impact that
state-of-the-art technology can have on the economic and social fabric of
small towns and villages.
The Kington Connected Community project will be sponsored by the government
and private and public-sector partners.
It will be monitored over a 12-month period by the Henley Centre, the social
and economic research company.
Kington, close to the Welsh border, has a population of 2,200 and serves an
agricultural area of 150 square miles.
During the next few months it will receive communications and computer
equipment worth more than Pounds 250,000, as well as financial support to
establish a 'telecentre' and provide training for business and computing
skills.
The Department of Trade and Industry, British Telecommunications, Apple
Computer and the Rural Development Commission are the lead partners in the
pilot scheme, which was awarded to Kington after competitive bids from a
number of other towns.
Kington will be equipped with a 'telecentre' and a 'town area network'. The
'telecentre' will contain about 15 Apple computers, plus high-speed data
links, teleconferencing facilities, and software for a wide range of
established and start-up businesses.
Kington's businesses, schools, clubs, tourist information office and shops
will be offered equipment linked to a local telecommunications network. This
will be upgraded by a connection to BT's ISDN2 service to give enhanced
data-transfer capacity.
Projects planned range from providing a common administrative back-up system
for five local primary schools to the provision of a single stock-control
system for a chain of three sports shops run from the town.
Mr Miles Swinburne, a local construction manager who helped put together
Kington's bid, said: 'People can see the writing on the wall for communities
like ours, and they want to use modern communications to do something about
it.'
The aim, he said, was to protect existing community activities and attract
new businesses to the town.
'We don't only want 'teleworkers' who want to work from the country, but
small high-tech companies run by people brought up in the area but who have
been sucked into the south-east because of the perception of remoteness and
inadequate communications,' he said.
</TEXT>
