<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / BMA accepts GP fundholding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE British Medical Association yesterday decided to relax its opposition to
general-practitioner fundholding, the most controversial aspect of the
government's National Health Service reforms.
While the association continues to believe that fund-holding has led to the
development of a two-tier health service, its annual representative meeting
in Torquay yesterday voted 189 to 140 for a motion declaring that 'given the
present reality' the association should no longer assert its opposition to
the scheme.
Twenty-five per cent of general practitioners are now in fundholding
practices and this is likely to rise to around 40 per cent next year. In
these circumstances the association would have been able to maintain
entrenched opposition only at the expense of dividing its own membership.
Fundholders have budgets from which they purchase hospital and other care on
behalf of their patients. There have been allegations that hospitals have
sometimes given preference to fundholders' patients on financial rather than
clinical grounds. Even some supporters of the scheme accept that it can
distort local health spending priorities.
But Dr John Rae, a member of the association's council who moved the
successful motion, told the conference that fundholding had become a reality
and by 'stating implausible opposition' the association implied that it
would not talk about the scheme. Fundholding affected all GPs, he said, and
the association had to be involved in negotiations on the issues it raised
for all its members.
While the decision will be welcomed by the government, it does not indicate
a collapse of the association's hostility to the health reforms. There is a
growing feeling in the association that the warnings it sounded when the
reforms were introduced in 1991 are being proved correct.
Dr Jeremy Lee-Potter, chairman of the association's council, said in his
opening speech to the conference: 'We did not believe that the government
would make enough money available to solve the widespread problems that were
bound to appear. The government has not provided enough money and the
problems have appeared.'
Large industrial organisations, he said, now recognised that structures
based on co-operation and teamwork were best, adding that the co-operation
in the health service was being lost by the commercial competition at the
heart of the reforms.
</TEXT>
