<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / Body Shop claims 'libel' cut profits
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A TELEVISION programme that questioned the commitment to animal welfare of
The Body Shop, the natural toiletries and cosmetics group, cost the company
Pounds 463,000, the High Court was told yesterday.
Mr Gordon Roddick, The Body Shop chairman, and Mrs Anita Roddick, managing
director, are suing Channel 4 and Fulcrum Productions for libel over the
programme broadcast in the Dispatches series last year.
Cross-examined by Mr Richard Rampton QC, for the defendants, Mr Roddick said
pre-tax profits for the first six months of the 1992-93 financial year were
Pounds 930,000 lower than the previous year. He said the company was
claiming that Pounds 463,000 in lost profits - including Pounds 360,000 from
that period - was attributable to the programme.
The defendants deny libel. The hearing was adjourned until today.
</TEXT>
