<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / High loan scheme take-up expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER BANKING CORRESPONDENT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKS EXPECT the reformed version of the government's Loan Guarantee Scheme
to attract greater involvement from both borrowers and lenders when it is
launched this week.
The British Bankers' Association yesterday said the scheme, which extends
the maximum loan for existing businesses from Pounds 100,000 to Pounds
250,000, would probably be attractive to companies trying to obtain debt to
trade into recovery.
Sir Nicholas Goodison, president of the association, said banks were
expecting 'some lively business' from the revised scheme, under which the
government guarantees banks against defaults on loans by small businesses.
Banks have been criticised for lending too little under the 12-year-old
scheme, although they argue that they have only responded to a lack of
demand. Banks are only allowed to use the scheme if they have exhausted
alternatives.
Mr Stuart White, chairman of the association's small-business committee,
said it was hard to predict the level of demand for the revised scheme.
However, he said the changes would make it particularly relevant for
companies emerging from recession.
Mr White said the scheme was likely to 'come into its own perfectly well'
for companies whose equity capital had been reduced by trading in recession
and were now seeking loan capital in order to finance increased orders.
Banks have yet to disclose the terms on which they will offer fixed-rate
loans when the revised scheme comes into effect on Thursday. The revisions
announced in the last Budget include the introduction of fixed-rate finance.
The altered scheme prohibits loans being offered to 'local service'
businesses such as small retailers, although 23 per cent of the Pounds 1.2bn
lent so far has gone to such enterprises.
</TEXT>
