<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / Sweden snubbed over Bosnia post
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, UN Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UN secretary general Boutros Boutros Ghali has offended Sweden, perhaps the
world organisation's most loyal supporter, by replacing the Swedish
commander of peacekeeping forces in Bosnia with a French officer, without
consulting Stockholm.
The nomination of General Jean Cot to succeed Lt General Lars-Eric Wahlgren,
which will take effect on July 1, was confirmed by the Security Council in
an exchange of letters made public yesterday.
But Mr Peter Osvald, Sweden's UN delegate, complained that Mr Boutros Ghali
made his decision without bothering to advise in advance either the Swedish
government or Gen Wahlgren, who has a distinguished career in UN
peacekeeping.
It appears the secretary general also neglected to inform the
troop-contributing countries other than France, with whom he arranged the
transfer of command during a visit to Paris last week.
Gen Wahlgren had been commander only since March. The Swedish parliament
only recently approved the dispatch of 1,000 troops to Bosnia.
It was not known whether they would be for general peacekeeping duty or
deployment in Moslem 'safe areas' that are badly in need of United Nations
forces. In any event, the change of command could delay their arrival.
French Lt Gen Philipe Morillon, who became something of a hero for defying
the Serbs to escort humanitarian aid to the beleaguered Moslems, is also
being replaced. His successor has not yet been named.
The possibility that UN peacekeeping operations might be terminated in the
absence of an early political settlement has been raised in a report to the
Security Council.
In recommending that the UN force mandate be extended for only three months,
to September 30, Mr Boutros Ghali emphasised that if the parties involved in
the conflict failed to demonstrate a commitment to a settlement, it would
not be worthwhile to use the UN's limited resources to maintain the
operation.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BAZ   Bosnia-Hercegovina, East Europe.
</CN>
