<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / UK accuses EC of 'plot' over fuel tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUXEMBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S environment minister, Mr John Gummer, claimed last night to have
defeated an EC ambush intended to get the UK to agree that a Community-wide
energy tax was a pre-condition for the Twelve to ratify the Rio climate
change convention.
As a result of the row, expected agreement on ratification of the convention
 -through which the EC commits itself to stabilising carbon dioxide
emissions at 1990 levels by 2000 - looked certain to be postponed.
Six EC member states led by Germany and the Netherlands said in March that
the Rio target was not possible without the tax, calling into question
ratification of the convention. In April, energy and environment ministers
from 11 member states agreed on the principle of an EC energy tax, although
finance ministers of the 12 earlier this month shelved further discussion of
the tax.
The tax, due originally to have started this year at Dollars 3 per barrel of
oil equivalent, is supposed to rise to Dollars 10 by 2000.
Mr Gummer said the Danish presidency 'tried to bounce us by getting a piece
of paper which said the 11 took one view but we took another'. He derided
the attempt as 'a plot that failed, happily', because even pro-tax member
states like Germany objected to 'the stitch-up', and doubters like Spain
underlined there was still no consensus on how the burden would be shared.
Mr Hans Alders, the Dutch environment minister, said the UK minister 'was at
another lunch' and that 'the British are still in an isolated position'. He
said a May 27 memorandum from Sir John Cope, the UK paymaster general, had
definitively ruled out Britain's acceptance of an EC-wide tax, and invited
'those member states who wished to do so to introduce a tax which is
compatible with the single market'.
The Dutch minister said the Commission would be bringing forward detailed
plans on 'burden-sharing' before the summer break, and the ratification
issue would not be settled before October.
Mr Gummer also claimed that at last week's Copenhagen summit, EC heads of
government 'said very clearly' that how to reach the emissions target was
for national governments to decide, as the UK had done by introducing fuel
and heating oil taxes.
Mr Svend Auken, the Danish chairman of the stormy meeting, described Mr
Gummer's interpretation of the Copenhagen conclusions as 'purely personal',
while Mr Ioannis Paleokrassas, EC environment commissioner, added that the
British minister's reading of Copenhagen was 'arbitrary'.
</TEXT>
