<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / Bosnians seek to end deadlock
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER, LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MEMBERS of Bosnia's multi-ethnic presidency said in Geneva yesterday that
they would be going to the Bosnian capital, Sarajevo, today to try to
persuade its current head, Mr Alija Izetbegovic, to rejoin the peace
negotiations.
Mr Franjo Boras, Croat head of a seven-strong presidency delegation to the
Geneva peace talks, said the Sarajevo meeting would be followed within a few
days by a second session 'elsewhere in Bosnia'.
Mr Izetbegovic, together with Mr Ejup Ganic, his vice-president, have so far
boycotted the talks on the proposed division of the country into a
confederation of three ethnic mini-states, which Mr Izetbegovic has
condemned as tantamount to genocide for the Moslems.
The international mediators, Lord Owen and Mr Thorvald Stoltenberg, are
hoping the new plan will at least guarantee the Moslems their own viable and
secure geographical entity.
It was not clear if the two mediators would attend the Sarajevo meeting, but
diplomats said both were expected to travel to the Croatian capital, Zagreb,
to be close at hand.
Mr Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader, said yesterday that Serbs and
Croats were close to an 'overall agreement' on Bosnia's ethnic division and
urged Moslem leaders to return to the negotiating table. Speaking after
talks with Mr Mate Boban, the Bosnian Croat leader. Mr Karadzic said the two
sides had agreed on everything except a map of the three ethnic mini-states
they are demanding.
'The only part that remained to be agreed is the map of the three republics
and both Serbs and Croats are ready to form their own states,' he said.
Earlier, Mr Karadzic had promised the Moslems nearly 30 per cent of Bosnia,
but warned that Serbs and Croats would not hesitate to carve up the country
between them if the Moslems did not negotiate. 'If they fail to do so,
Bosnia will in effect be split into two parts. Some of the Moslems will
remain with us, while the Croats will get the others,' he told the Yugoslav
news agency, Tanjug.
</TEXT>
