<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / German left-wing terrorists warned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Germany will continue the fight against terrorism, following the arrest of a
prominent member of the Red Army Faction, the interior ministry said
yesterday, writes Judy Dempsey in Berlin.
The arrest of Ms Birgit Hogefeld, a prominent member of the RAF left-wing
terrorist group, and the shooting dead of Mr Wolfgang Grams by the
anti-terrorist unit, is a welcome boost for security forces.
Ms Hogefeld was arrested at the weekend in the eastern state of
Mecklenburg-Vorpommern. A police officer was shot dead during a shoot out in
an operation aimed at trying to find the remaining hard core of 20 RAF
members.
The guerrilla movement, set up in the 1970s, was virtually dormant in the
1980s, but re-emerged after German unification in 1990.
It was responsible for murdering Hans-Martin Schleyer, president of west
Germany's employers' federation in 1977, and Mr Detlev Rohwedder, who was
head of the Treuhand, the agency charged with restructuring and privatising
eastern German industry.
</TEXT>
