<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 93 / Boeing challenges Airbus with improved 737 models
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BOEING, the world's biggest manufacturer of commercial jets, yesterday
decided to offer a new family of 737 twin-engine airliners to challenge the
European Airbus consortium's range of twin-engine aircraft.
Although the 737 has been the world's best-selling jet with more than 3,000
aircraft ordered to date and more than 2,500 delivered, Boeing has faced
increasing competition in this market from the Airbus A320 and its bigger
A321 derivative.
The decision was taken in Seattle by the Boeing board, which said it would
offer three sizes of improved 737 aircraft, including a 105-seater, a
130-seater and a 150-seater.
Boeing said that a formal launch of the development programme would hinge on
the company's winning sufficient initial orders. It said it had started
working with more than 30 airlines in 1991 on an improved 737 family.
Airbus has made inroads in the narrow-body market by launching new,
technically more advanced airliners.
Last year, it struck a significant blow against Boeing by winning a Dollars
2bn (Pounds 1.3bn) order for 50 A320 jets from United Airlines, a
traditional Boeing customer.
Airbus also raised the competitive stakes this month at the Paris Air Show
when it launched the development programme for the A319, a smaller, 125-seat
variant of the A320.
The original 737 programme was launched in 1965. The new 737 derivative will
involve a bigger wing, improved powerplant and advanced systems to provide
more range, speed and payload to compete against the improvements introduced
by the Airbus 150-180-seat narrow-body jets.
The bigger engines will be developed by the CFM partnership between General
Electric of the US and Snecma of France.
Boeing had considered developing an entirely new aircraft rather than a 737
derivative. It rejected that option on the grounds of market timing and of
the much higher development costs.
Developing a completely new narrow-body aircraft would cost an estimated
Dollars 3bn-Dollars 4bn, while the cost of an improved derivative is put at
about Dollars 1.5bn.
Boeing had been under increasing pressure to offer airline customers
improved versions of the 737 in the second half of the decade to coincide
with the expected recovery in the world aircraft market. Boeing said last
night that the first aircraft would be delivered in 1997.
</TEXT>
<XX>
