<DATE>930628
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 93 / Survey of World Automotive Suppliers (3): Cutting costs with
gusto / Profile of Jose Ignacio Lopez de Arriortua
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Jose Ignacio Lopez de Arriortua, Volkswagen's new chief of production and
purchasing, is the most controversial figure to have made waves in the world
automotive parts industry in many years, writes Martin Dickson.
A Spaniard from the Basque country, his fame stems from May of last year
when General Motors plucked him out of its successful European operations to
help the huge task of turning around its loss-making North American
automotive operations.
Mr Lopez, appointed as GM's head of worldwide parts purchasing, set about
the task with such gusto, and using such unusual methods, that he stirred up
immense controversy among GM's US supplier base. And he caused no less of a
stir in March this year when, following five days of tug-of-war between GM
and Volkswagen, he quit the US company for the German one.
Since joining Volkswagen, he has announced plans to build a 'laboratory
production facility' in Spain which would test new methods of producing a
small car in less than 12 hours.
Vokswagen and GM have become embroiled in a heated legal dispute over Mr
Lopez, with the US company accusing him of taking with him proprietary
information which belongs to it. He denies this.
Whatever the truth, there is no denying the positive effect Mr Lopez had on
GM's cost base during his 10 months in North America. He is estimated to
have saved the company well over Dollars 1bn by forcing suppliers to cut
their prices.
However, his psychological impact on GM may have been even more valuable.
Arguably more than any other single individual, he brought home to both GM's
employees and outside vendors that the company had finally begun changing
its bureaucratic ways, and there could be no backsliding to the old order.
He was personally unconventional. He called his staff 'warriors,' encouraged
them to eat a diet high in fruit and low in potatoes, and said he would wear
his watch on his right arm until GM was back in profit. He lectured
suppliers on the supposed 'crisis' facing the US motor industry and sent
'hit squads' of productivity experts into suppliers' factories to advise on
improving their performance.
All this was designed to force GM into a new, and far less cosy relationship
with its US suppliers. Mr Lopez demanded big price cuts from them, of up to
20 per cent or more, but in return promised long term contracts.
He had already had plenty of experience in changing supplier/assembler
relationships. As head of parts purchasing for GM in Europe, based in
Russelsheim, Germany, between 1988 and 1992, he was a key member of the team
which turned GM Europe from losses into one of the world's most profitable
vehicle businesses.
He sharply altered GM's relations with European suppliers, shifting a large
quantity of work from high cost German components companies to cheaper
manufacturers in other parts of the region.
Such a history made him particularly attractive to Volkswagen, which needs
to drastically reduce its cost structure. Mr Ferdinand Piech, chairman of
the Volkswagen management board, said in a recent interview: 'We got to know
each other and established we think alike . . .For Lopez and me it is not a
question of money. It's about maintaining Europe as a centre for
manufacturing industry, to defend it and make it number one in the world
again.'
