<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 93 / Foreign Exchange and Money Markets: Bank under pressure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE German Bundesbank will find itself in the international firing line
again this week as its European partners pile on the pressure for lower
German interest rates ahead of its council meeting on Thursday, writes
Gillian Tett.
In spite of the continued inflationary pressures in Germany, there is
speculation that the forthcoming G-7 summit might prod the Bundesbank into
action.
But with the D-Mark continuing to soften against the dollar and European
currencies, the markets remain wary of predicting how fast or how far the
Bundesbank might move.
Following French calls for a concerted interest rate cut last week, the
markets will be watching the Bank of France closely to see whether it is
prepared to instigate any further independent rate cuts.
With French official rates now below German rates for the first time in 26
years, many economists doubt that France could implement rapid cuts in the
face of continuing Bundesbank intransigence.
Nevertheless, the deepening recession in France has led some observers to
interpret last week's statements by Mr Edmond Alphandery, the French finance
minister, as an indication that France might be willing to move ahead with
bold rate cuts.
'All this puts the focus on the extent to which the French really need the
Germans to cut their rates,' said Ms Alison Cottrell, international
economist with Midland Global Markets.
Following the slight weakening of the French franc late last week, there are
fears that any rapid move could trigger selling of the French currency.
The yen is expected to remain volatile in the run up to the Japanese general
election, in spite of bouncing back from some its earlier losses last week.
Continuing tension over Japan's huge trade surplus with the US is expected
to make the yen-dollar rate sensitive to speculative movements ahead of next
week's G7 summit in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ   Germany, EC.
    FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
