<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 93 / US Money and Credit: Treasury prices advance as inflation
picture brightens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AT 6.7 per cent, Treasury bond yields are once again close to their
historical lows, and three factors are driving prices up and interest rates
down.
First, the inflation picture has brightened since the dark days of early
1993, when prices were rising at a rate of around 4 per cent per year.
Recent data showed inflation slowing to nearer 3 per cent and all the latest
indicators point to an economic recovery that should remain sluggish and
relatively inflation-free.
Second, the Federal Reserve has put on an excellent show of
anti-inflationary fervour during the past two weeks. A series of
well-placed, if occasionally clumsy, leaks may have enraged traditionalists
at the Fed who prefer the central bank's policy positions to remain private,
but they sent a clear and unequivocal message to the financial markets: the
Fed stands ready to raise interest rates at the first hint of an upturn in
inflation.
Normally, the possibility of a Fed tightening would send bond yields sharply
higher - and it did, earlier this month.
But recently investors and dealers have come to take a more considered view
of the Fed's unusually public musings. Now, they are relieved that the
anti-inflation credibility of the Fed chairman, Mr Alan Greenspan, has been
restored. After all, it was only a few weeks ago the market was worrying
that Mr Greenspan had become too familiar with the Clinton administration.
Third, President Clinton's economic package continues to make its way
through Congress and looks as if it will emerge with its central
deficit-reducing features more or less intact.
Admittedly, the bill only squeaked through the Senate on Thursday, thanks to
the clinching vote of vice-president Gore - hardly a ringing endorsement of
the President's economic policies.
The Clinton package is important not only because it is the first serious
attempt by the federal government to tackle its huge budget deficit.
The economic plan is also expected to act initially as a brake on economic
growth - something that even the Clinton administration admits is likely.
This is good news for bond investors.
Also, some analysts believe the package will ensure that interest rates
remain low. Mr Maury Harris, chief economist at Wall Street securities house
PaineWebber, is one of them.
He believes the Fed will hold off from using higher interest rates to slow
inflationary growth because tax rises and spending cuts will do the job for
them.
Mr Harris says: 'Considering the likelihood of a more restrictive fiscal
policy in the form of higher taxes and some spending restraint, maintaining
the 3 per cent Federal Funds rate probably will be the most sensible course
of action for the central bank at its August and September meetings.'
Moreover, 'if the tempo of reported economic activity and inflation picks up
a bit in June from the very modest May pace, it would not make sense this
year to try reigning in growth with higher interest rates when more taxes
and some federal spending restraint are just around the corner.'
Mr Harris need not worry, if the forecasts for this week's economic data are
to be believed. Economists are predicting the May leading indicators and
single-family home sales (both out tomorrow) will be flat or lower, that May
manufacturing orders (Wednesday) will be down 0.8 per cent, and that June
unemployment (Friday) will be 7.0 per cent, up from 6.9 per cent in May.
If the economic forecasts prove correct and the Clinton package stays on
schedule to be passed by Congress in August, then expect bond yields to come
down further over the next few weeks, setting new record lows in the
process.
</TEXT>
<XX>
