<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 93 / UK Gilts: Yields fall on strong institutional buying
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YIELDS continued to tumble on the back of strong buying by overseas and
domestic institutions as expectations improved about the UK inflation
outlook.
Several big institutions were reported to be switching out of French
government bonds into gilts, on the grounds that the UK securities look
relatively cheap.
Even with this Wednesday's biggest-ever gilt auction looming, the omens for
more gilt-yield reductions in the coming months look reasonably good. That
is assuming signs of price pressures in the economy remain thin on the
ground.
During the past week, many classes of gilts saw a yield reduction of about
10 basis points, with the moves being especially pronounced at the long end
of the gilt curve.
Comments at the end of the week by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, that
he was unlikely to cut base rates in the near future cut the momentum of the
uptrend for short-dated securities.
While French 10-year government bonds have seen yields drop nearly 50 basis
points in the past month, gilts have almost matched this movement, with a
yield fall of about 35 basis points.
With 10-year gilt yields now about 7.7 per cent, compared with about 6.7 per
cent for comparable French bonds, many investors can be excused for
switching into the UK instruments.
The difference between 10-year gilt yields and the comparable figure for
German bonds has come down to about 1 percentage point from about 1.3
percentage points a month ago.
Indications last week that the pace of the UK recovery has become more muted
in recent months only added to the enthusiasm for gilt purchases, on the
basis that a weak upturn is less likely to spark inflation.
At the same time, there is little evidence that the UK is moving into a
second leg of recession. This would be bad for the gilt market, which wants
modest growth to erode the Pounds 50bn gap between government spending and
revenues.
The latest Confederation of British Industry survey of manufacturers, issued
on Friday, was music to the ears of gilts practitioners. It showed that,
after strong first-quarter growth, many companies have in the past two
months become less confident about increasing sales volumes.
The survey also indicated that inflationary pressures were subdued, with
only few companies thinking they will increase prices over the next few
months.
Mr Leslie Gunde, chief economist at engineering company GKN and a member of
the Treasury's industrial prospects committee, said: 'The recovery is going
to be slower than previous upturns, but it is definitely happening.'
Mr Ian Shepherdson, a bond specialist at brokers Greenwell Montagu, said the
gilt market was generally cheered by Mr Clarke's approach in his first month
as chancellor. 'He seems to be a growth man, but not so much that he's going
to be irresponsible (by cutting interest rates quickly and sparking
inflation)'.
A sign of the interest in gilts last week was that, out of a tranche of
Pounds 850m of bonds provided to the market by the Bank of England, the
long-dated securities sold out within hours.
While the market snapped up the Pounds 400m worth of 8 per cent stock
maturing in 2013, there were fewer buyers for Pounds 300m of five-year bonds
and Pounds 150m of long-dated index-linked securities.
Only on Friday did the market appear fully to wake up to the implications of
this week's gilt auction, when the Bank will be selling Pounds 3.25bn of 8
per cent bonds due in 2003.
The small subsequent rise in yields along the curve - except for securities
above the 15-year mark - was probably partly in anticipation of the
price-reducing effects of such a large stock coming on to the market.
Even with the effects of the Pounds 3bn or so a month of gilts likely to be
sold over the next year, Mr Steven Bell of Deutsche Bank believes 10-year
gilt yields will continue to fall to 7.3 per cent by next summer. He reckons
five-year yields will also come down over this period, from 7.05 per cent to
6.4 per cent.
</TEXT>
