<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 93 / International Company News: Stone plans to raise Dollars
386m in note issues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
STONE Container, the Chicago-based international packaging and paper group,
is raising USDollars 386m with two note issues and considering spinning off
its newsprint and groundwood papers operations through a public equity
issue.
Stone bought its Canadian, British and German newsprint and packaging
operations in 1989 for CDollars 2.6bn (USDollars 2bn). It detached the
profitable Europa Carton business in Germany, making it a direct subsidiary
of Stone Container, Chicago.
The newsprint mills in eastern Canada, Arizona and Ellesmere Port, near
Liverpool, were soon battered by the global recession.
Stone has about USDollars 4bn debt and is raising USDollars 250m by the
private placement of notes yielding 9 per cent and convertible into common
stock at USDollars 11.15 a share
It is also raising about USDollars 150m with a five-year note at 12.625 per
cent interest. The net proceeds of the issues will be about USDollars 386m.
The company confirmed it was pursuing a spin-off of its newsprint interests
into a new public company as 'an attractive option'.
The newsprint unit would include the Canadian, US and UK mills. A share
issue would raise about USDollars 250m in new equity. The unit would have
annual sales of around USDollars 1bn with annual capacity of 1.7m tonnes of
newsprint and groundwood papers.
Mr Stanley Ho, the Hong Kong hotel magnate, plans to buy Toronto's luxury
Sutton Place Kempinski from a group of German investors for a reported price
below CDollars 40m, or less than half book value.
The hotel has been in receivership since December. Mr Ho bought a similar
luxury hotel in Vancouver in 1988 and contracted management to Meridien, the
Air France subsidiary. He is also a shareholder in Meridien.
He has also contracted management of Sutton Place to Meridien.
</TEXT>
