<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 93 / The Lex Column: Junk bonds
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The revival in junk bonds over the past year suggests that market memories
are indeed short. Falling US deposit rates have forced investors away from
the relative security of the banks towards bond and equity markets.
Lacklustre performance there has tempted the brave back into high yield
paper. There is a case to be made for the move. Many of the junk bonds
currently being issued are on much more conservative terms than in the
heyday of 1987-89. Earnings are bottoming out rather than peaking. The risks
of corporate failure are undoubtedly lower.
Yet the substantial risks may not have been fully considered by buyers
disinclined to be fussy. Interest cover of two times on new leveraged
buy-outs is hardly generous. A rise in short rates would both tempt money
out of the junk market and put pressure on bond yields. Valuation criteria
for junk have been notoriously elastic. With little firm notion of good
value, prices could thus fall rapidly if sentiment changed. Mr Michael
Milken made a career and a fortune from the proposition that junk bonds were
mis-priced. Others lost vast amounts on the same notion. The clear winners
in junk were those companies which retired cheap equity in the late 1980s
with high yield bonds, survived, and are now buying back that junk cheaply
with more expensive shares. Investors who now regard junk as a double-digit
coupon bank deposit can expect little sympathy if it all turns sour.
</TEXT>
<XX>
