<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 93 / Tietmeyer plays down weak D-Mark and hints at rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BUNDESBANK sees the current weakness of the D-Mark as part of a
'normalisation' process and not the start of a run on the currency, Mr Hans
Tietmeyer, its vice-president, said yesterday.
In a radio interview he also reiterated the commitment of the German central
bank to bringing down interest rates when conditions are appropriate - a
statement which, in conjunction with his apparent nonchalance about the
currency, may stimulate hopes of further early cuts in interest rates. These
could come as early as Thursday when the Bundesbank's policymaking council
meets in Leipzig, some economists believe.
'The current exchange rate situation is in my opinion thoroughly appropriate
for the German economy,' Mr Tietmeyer said, arguing that after the
correction of exchange rates within the European exchange rate mechanism,
the recent weakening of the D-Mark was a 'normalisation process' as money
flowed out of the D-Mark back to the original currencies.
'We must take care to ensure that this normalisation doesn't turn into
something entirely different,' he said.
Mr Tietmeyer said that markets had confidence in the Bundesbank's monetary
policy 'as they have always had,' and therefore he believed there would not
be a run on the D-Mark. But he pointed out that investors took account of
Germany's entire 'policy mix', including pay and fiscal policy as well as
social considerations. Decisions taken by the government, by unions and by
businesses were all important.
The statements appear designed to exert more pressure on the political
establishment to agree meaningful cuts in public expenditure. Mr Theo
Waigel, finance minister, is finalising proposals for spending cuts in order
to tackle government borrowing requirements which are expected to reach 7.5
per cent of gross national product this year.
'We certainly don't want to keep interest rates unnecessarily high,' Mr
Tietmeyer said. 'Our main concern is to avoid the situation where if we cut
short-term interest rates, this leads to a rise in rates at the long end of
the yield curve' (ie higher long-term interest rates).
He warned against trying to stimulate Germany's economy via rate cuts,
saying that could be counterproductive. 'But this doesn't at all mean that
interest rates at the short-term cannot be brought down further.' The D-Mark
last week sank to a post-war low against the yen, and fell to DM1.70 against
the US dollar, from DM1.62 over two weeks. Interest rates in France fell
below those in Germany for the first time in 26 years, leading to
suggestions that the French franc could replace the D-Mark as anchor of the
ERM.
See Lex
Balance tips in favour of rate cut, Page 20
</TEXT>
