FT  28 JUN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If you have had a hard day and laughter is your object you may be best
advised to pop out to the video shop or even (provided you have plenty of
cash and can tolerate the smell of hot dogs and the chatter of the audience)
the cinema. Failing that there are three sitcom repeats: So Haunt Me (8.00
BBC1) in which Miriam Karlin plays a Jewish mother-in-law ghost, score six
out of 10; Waiting For God (8.30 BBC1) with Graham Crowden and Stephanie
Cole playing a couple of bolshie pensioners in a retirement home, score nine
out of 10; and Surgical Spirit (8.30 C4) which stars the violently mugging
Nichola McAuliffe as a surgeon, score four out of 10. In the last of its
present series Horizon surveys some of the theories about the origins of
life: primordial soup, comets and meteorites delivering life from the skies,
or hydrothermal vents from beneath the ocean (8.10 BBC2). Cancer specialist
Rob Buckman presents the third of four programmes which consider the claims
and achievements of conventional and alternative health care, Magic Or
Medicine? (9.00 C4).
