<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 93 / Global link set up to issue information
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN electronic World Press Centre designed to link organisations issuing
information with journalists all over the world has been created with
venture-capital backing.
The London-based computer centre, which is already operational, has the
support of organisations such as the World Bank and Unesco.
Governments, international agencies, businesses and pressure groups will
send their press information electronically to the London centre, and it can
be read electronically anywhere by journalists.
Unlike normal day-to-day storage, information in the World Press Centre is
organised in a series of electronic pigeonholes. Journalists interested in
climactic change, international trade or health, for instance, can simply
dip into the relevant pigeonhole to see whether there have been any releases
on their subject.
Press releases can be made available instantly all over the world to
journalists, normally at local telephone call rates. There will be also be
multi-language versions.
Former journalist Mr Peter Thompson, founder of the centre and who trained
as an economist, has been working on the system for eight years.
He believes he is well on the way to beating the 'chicken and egg' problem -
information providers using the system only when they are confident that
newspapers and broadcasters are also using it.
Lord Grenfell, chief of external affairs at the European office of the World
Bank, said: 'Our feeling is that we now have a system into which we can feed
a great deal of information of interest to the end users and indeed we are
now feeding in such material on a regular basis.'
Mr Rod Fenwick, a senior marketing executive at Atex, the supplier of
computerised newsroom systems, said the company is investigating the
possibility of adding the World Press Centre software to its systems as
added value.
In the developed world the operation will be a profit-making venture but the
developing world will be charged at cost. Subscriptions will be about Pounds
10 per week for each individual using the centre.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ   United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
