<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 93 / Pressure grows on ITV over news slot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POLITICAL opposition to the ITV companies' plans to move News at Ten to the
early evening is likely to increase this week.
The government has made clear its displeasure over the proposed move and has
warned that it may refuse to allow any latitude over the future ownership of
television news organisations.
Under the 1990 Broadcasting Act 51 per cent of ITN has to move to non-ITV
ownership by the end of 1994. Following the ITN reorganisation earlier this
year which brought in Reuters as a shareholder, the remaining ITV owners
thought the government could be persuaded to change its mind.
They hoped that bringing in another outside shareholder, such as a US
network, would be seen as an acceptable level of outside investment and that
the ITV shareholders - Carlton, Central, London Weekend, Granada, Scottish
and Anglia - would be allowed to retain control.
It is now being made clear by Downing Street that if News at Ten disappears,
and with it the platform it often gives the Commons for historic votes live
on air between 10pm and 10.30pm, the letter of the Broadcasting Act on ITN
ownership would be enforced.
ITV wants to move News at Ten to 6.30pm or 7pm because its present slot
interrupts films and drama beginning after the 9pm 'adult' watershed and
because of what it sees as increasing competition from Channel 4.
The Broadcasting Act took away the power of the Independent Television
Commission to set specific time slots for programmes although the ITC plans
to do everything it can to block the move.
Some people in ITV would also like to remove the ITN brand name from its
bulletins on ITV and just give it a credit at the end like any other
programme supplier.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Independent Television News.
</CO>
<XX>
