<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUN 93 / Major intervenes over market-testing delays
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR WILLIAM Waldegrave, the public service minister, has called in Mr John
Major to speed up the much-vaunted programme of bringing private-sector
competition to government activities.
Mr Waldegrave has been unable alone to push the initiative for-ward, and has
been forced to call on the prime minister to remind departments of the
initiative's importance.
Mr Major will give fresh impetus to the market-testing initiative by telling
Whitehall departments which have slipped severely behind schedule that they
must treat it as a priority. Up to a dozen departments are expected to
receive the Downing Street order to make better progress. They include the
Home Office, the Ministry of Agriculture and the Department of Trade and
Industry.
News of Mr Major's intervention came as Labour highlighted embarrassing
delays in the programme for market testing.
Ms Majorie Mowlam, Labour's public service spokeswoman, said government
information showed that four mainstream departments had failed to complete a
single market-testing exercise since November. The four departments - the
DTI, the Department for Education, the Scottish Office and the Department of
Transport - are due to have completed market-testing more than Pounds 130m
of Civil Service activities by the end of September.
Concern that this year's programme has fallen so far behind schedule has
raised questions over its extension. Mr Waldegrave has been planning to
extend competition in an ambitious range of areas from the late autumn.
Contracts already put out to tender include some core Whitehall work such as
the Treasury's economic forecasting and data collection as well as support
work including information technology consultancy, and legal and estate
management services.
Some senior civil servants are said to claim responsibility for delaying
progress in contracting-out, but the most serious factor is confusion over
the impact of regulations designed to protect the rights of workers in
takeovers and mergers.
The Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of Employment) 1981 regulations
guarantee the jobs and pay of the existing workforce in many cases when work
is contracted out. As the regulations implement the European Community
Acquired Rights Directive they cannot be removed by UK legislation.
In a letter leaked earlier this year, Mr Michael Bichard, the chief
executive of the Benefits Agency, complained that the Cabinet Office had
failed to answer key questions over the issue.
There has also been some criticism from within Downing Street that Sir Peter
Levene, head of the efficiency unit, has not dealt with the difficulty more
decisively.
Ms Mowlam said that the stalling of the programme amounted to a 'de facto
moratorium caused by departmental confusion and uncertainty, and William
Waldegrave's lack of political clout'.
</TEXT>
